{"cursor":"7665","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn commutative ring theory, a branch of mathematics, the 'radical of an ideal' I\nis an ideal such that an element x is in the radical if some power of x is in I.\nA 'radical ideal' (or 'semiprime ideal') is an ideal that is its own radical\n(this can be phrased as being a fixed point of an operation on ideals called\n'radicalization'). The radical of a primary ideal is prime.\n\nRadical ideals defined here are generalized to noncommutative rings in the\nSemiprime ring article.\n","linknr":170,"url":"Radical_of_an_ideal","recorded":1362896642,"links":22,"instances":["commutative_algebra","mathematics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Ideals"],"headings":["Definition","Examples","Properties","Applications","See also","Notes","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/c/9/4c928e7f21c43c696281ef4349b5046e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/5/3/35351ab66e24c1de5069f3641f183ad0.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/9/9/199e770aefdf9e1969110b945e19e6ef.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/c/9/4c928e7f21c43c696281ef4349b5046e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/c/9/4c928e7f21c43c696281ef4349b5046e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/a/2/ea2e1a3cd0f24e62cd52ba7a29e18e69.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/e/d/aed0d0cee7abc7fd853accc87914f681.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/c/0/6c0c0f6b9a6710b9e78f6d23806f1f9a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/1/e/01eea2c97b7016f8b1d32cec91e85538.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/b/c/ebc706c0f0d5d022c558a6c6aa33878e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/a/c/8ac56ed61c1c0337ac96022258767dd9.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/0/0/c006ed58daa8bd8c4120b37b5b560ec0.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/2/e/32eda095c9b324a5c8866c9a1fcc33d1.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/0/8/d08fdcfe363cda18e299f8882c318515.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/0/1/101544deba86e212bff9929000efd2d8.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/4/9/549543ef8a969023f61a95717ebd5760.png","//upload.wik